#1312: I do not want to start a war on the internet. I am not an opponent of greek life. I think any organization whether its greek, athletic, or club that brings students together is a great thing. However, I saw something today that really made me sick. I don't know if it was meant to be funny, satirical, or serious, but it was a fraternity member bashing someone not in a fraternity (a "geed"). He said that people in fraternities are basically better than people that arent. He said that people in fraternities party harder, get laid more, are more successful, and overall "better" than people who are not because rush events are meant for members of the frat to judge the character of people rushing. Only those with the best character are in fraternities and get the chance to party and live like champions. Again, I dont dislike people in fraternities or sororities but i think the attitude that you are better than someone or your party is so cool because you didnt let a bunch of people in. I feel the same way when I go to south beach. Ive gone into the VIP and the music is the same, there might be a free drink but you are still the same distance from the dj and really you just paid extra money to feel like you are above people.I know i am not the best looking, richest, or nicest person on the planet. Thats why I always try to helpful and include someone who looks like they might be feeling left out in what i do. There are lot of great people and some of my friends in greek life, but the whole having to feel better about yourself by having to put someone else down is kind of sickening and I can not comprehend how people enjoy that attitude.

#1258: At #1183 I'm glad that you have a sense of urgency in life, regardless of whether people think it's too extreme or not. When you rest, rest like a champ because you deserve better than some half-assed, stressful excuse of a study break. Conversely,  when you work, work like a boss, with a sense of urgency, because you owe it to yourself not to waste all of that amazing restful rest you got for the sake of working harder. Carpe diem, seize the day. If the sun has gone down, we might not get tomorrow, so do it tonight.

data.message: I'm an Econ/ Poli Sci major and Spanish/Business Admin minor, if you need help with any of those types of classes feel free to message me! If not, you can always find free tutors at the University of Miami - Academic Resource Center!!!

College is a different ball game. Your peers aren't in your same class so there is less motivation to press on, on the work. If I were you, I would be telling myself that I am able to get the work done and do a good job at it at the same time. The only person that can prevent you from doing excellently in your work is you. A change in mindset will set you free of the limitations in your mind as to what you are capable of. Stay classy.

get involved with something you are really passionate about. There are a lot of organizations on campus or start your own. It is incredible the difference it will make in your life across the board. Good luck!

I used to feel the exact same way. Took me 2+ years to realize that keeping up with classes should be a top priority over blending in with this school. It's important to keep yourself involved and really make your time at this school worth it, but before pursuing that, you wanna have a firm foundation with classes first. It may not seem like it, but most professors out there want to help you and they take notice when you meet them during their office hours. I know right now it may seem like you're alone throughout the semester but you're really not.  Its a professor's job to encourage you as a student to go beyond any expectations of you; and they're proud to do it. Remember that and you'll do fine here. Welcome to the U and good luck!

The adjustment from high school to college is always hard especially with the heavy workload and demanding curriculum here at UM, it's you're first year and you will soon get in the groove and figure out what study habits works for you. You have to eliminate all the distractions here and make use of the academic resources we have. We've all been here and I understand your frustration but take it easy and maybe working with other smart kids in the class will help, good luck
Keep ur head up n visit a councilor
I would also just google time management and dorm organization etc..those things can help you
Visit professor office hours. Helps alot
If you ever need help with any of the science classes (I'm a neuroscience major) or just want a study buddy for motivation, feel free to message me!
Sounds like me too

i'm kind of in the same boat but i know that for the most part it's really because i haven't been applying myself the way i did in high school, i don't know if the same is true for you or not. sometimes you just need a little inspiration. message me if you ever want to talk about it or need a study buddy
